Comment: In this game I will continue to use the d4 opening which has proven to be effective against most players here on GK, I want to thank eesther for the challenge, as he is undefeated to everyone here besides myself.
d5 is a solid move for center control
This is a book move and is made most of the time, depending on how black plays, Nf3 was considered also.
protects the center pawn
Now I play the other move now, Nc3 was also a move I liked more than c5.
Black continues to develop Nf6
my second N is developed to Nc3
a6 is played by black, I thought developing another minor piece would have been better, But He had a reason for this move I am sure.
I play e3 protecting my d4 pawn and opening way for my lsb to be developed.
b5 played protected by pawn on a6 and c6. This also allows Black to develop his pieces on his Q side.
I now advance pawn  to c5 and have a fine wall of connected pawns. My other thought was to get castled quickly by developing my lsb.
develops his N in front of his Q. I thought he might of played Bg4 here.
I add another protector to my c5 pawn.
a5 is played which attacks pawn on b4
I decide to take here thinking to take is a mistake. By taking here I actually shift tempo to his favor I believe.
Q takes pawn  and I wonder how I can defend this move. he took this move over taking with his rook, which could have been played and not getting his Q out early. The Q takes seems to be best.
this simple move does the job to protect the loss of my R if I had left his attack of a skewer not stopped.
e5 is played attacking the center.
lsb is developed and now gives me a way to castle if I decide too. Right now I question if this is best place for my piece. My N is pinned and Bfd3 was my other move I had to choose from
I believe I said nice move after Ne4 was played. thinking I should have had my lsb on d3 here to take his N.
